<section id="section-4">
<title> Variable force
</title>
<section id="section-4a">

<para id="element-4a"><term>Problem 4 : </term>
Velocity - time plot of the motion of a particle of 1 kg from t = 2s to t = 6s, is as shown in figure. FInd the work done by all the forces (in Joule) on the particle during this time interval.</para>
<para id="element-5">
<figure id="fig-5">
<title> Velocity - time plot </title>
<media id="idp3131312" alt=""><image src="../../media/wkeq1.gif" mime-type="image/gif"/></media>
</figure>
</para>
<para id="element-7"><term>Solution : </term>
We are required to find work by all the forces, operating on the particle. No information about force is given. However, states of motion at end points can be read from the given plot. The "work - kinetic energy" theorem is independent of intermediate detail. From the plot. we have :
<m:math>
		<m:msub>
			<m:mi> v </m:mi>
			<m:mi> i </m:mi>
		</m:msub>
	</m:math>
 = 2 m/s and 
<m:math>
		<m:msub>
			<m:mi> v </m:mi>
			<m:mi> f </m:mi>
		</m:msub>
	</m:math>
 = 6 m/s. Now, applying theorem for the end conditions, we get the work by all forces, acting on the particle :
</para>
<para id="element-8">
<m:math display="block">
